\title{PITS: Power of Interrupted Time Series studies}
\description{
The package provides a complete workflow for ITS power analysis:

\strong{Step 1 - Estimate nuisance parameters from pre-intervention data}

Use \code{\link[=estimate_its_params]{estimate_its_params()}} to estimate \code{baseline}, \code{sigma} (residual SD),
and \code{rho} (AR(1) autocorrelation) from a pre-intervention time series.
Individual functions \code{\link[=estimate_baseline]{estimate_baseline()}}, \code{\link[=estimate_sigma]{estimate_sigma()}},
\code{\link[=estimate_rho]{estimate_rho()}}, and \code{\link[=estimate_trend]{estimate_trend()}} are also available.

\strong{Step 2 - Calculate power via Monte Carlo simulation}

Use \code{\link[=calculate_power]{calculate_power()}} (single site) or \code{\link[=calculate_power_multi]{calculate_power_multi()}}
(multiple sites) to estimate the probability of detecting a specified
intervention effect for a given study design.

\strong{Step 3 - Optimise the design}

Use \code{\link[=power_sweep]{power_sweep()}} to evaluate power across a range of post-intervention
durations, and \code{\link[=run_power_grid]{run_power_grid()}} for full factorial sensitivity analyses.
Visualise results with \code{\link[=plot_power_curve]{plot_power_curve()}} and \code{\link[=plot_power_heatmap]{plot_power_heatmap()}}.

\strong{Convenience wrappers}

\code{\link[=run_its_power]{run_its_power()}} replicates the interactive experience of the original
\code{its_power_tool.R} script. \code{\link[=estimate_and_calculate]{estimate_and_calculate()}} chains parameter
estimation and power calculation in a single call.
}
\details{
Tools for estimating the statistical power of Interrupted Time Series (ITS)
designs, with a focus on healthcare applications.
